Compound.comment: Coenzyme A (CoA) is a ubiquitous cofactor found in bacteria, plants, and animals. CoA participates in a large number of enzymatic reactions central to intermediary metabolism, including the oxidation of fatty acids, carbohydrates, and amino acids. Coenzyme A is the common acyl carrier in prokaryotic and eukaryotic cells, and is required for a multitude of reactions for both biosynthetic and degradative pathways [Rubio06].
